<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18440205-793">
               <interp inst="t18440205-793" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18440205"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18440205-793" type="date" value="18440205"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18440205-793-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-793-18440205 t18440205-793-offence-1 t18440205-793-verdict-1"></join>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18440205-793-charge-2" targOrder="Y" targets="def2-793-18440205 t18440205-793-offence-1 t18440205-793-verdict-2"></join>
               <p>793. <persName id="def1-793-18440205" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-793-18440205" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-793-18440205" type="age" value="26"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-793-18440205" type="surname" value="JANES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-793-18440205" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">GEORGE JANES</hi>
                  </persName> and <persName id="def2-793-18440205" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def2-793-18440205" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-793-18440205" type="age" value="25"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-793-18440205" type="surname" value="SMITH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-793-18440205" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">WILLIAM SMITH</hi>
                  </persName> were indicted for<rs id="t18440205-793-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18440205-793-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18440205-793-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="animalTheft"></interp> steal<lb></lb>ing 1 gelding, value 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.; 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., and 1 mare, 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.; 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., the property of <persName id="t18440205-name-1435" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1435" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1435" type="surname" value="PERSHOUSE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1435" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18440205-793-offence-1 t18440205-name-1435"></join>William Pershouse</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HORRY</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440205-name-1436" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1436" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1436" type="surname" value="HARRIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1436" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM HARRIS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am inspector of places for slaughtering horses for St. George the Martyr, Southwark. On the 2nd of Jan., Mr. Winkley, a licensed horse slaughterer, sent for me to take two horses—I went to his premises about half-past eight in the morning, and saw a mare and gelding, which I have since ordered to be given up to Mr. Pershouse's man—the prisoners were there—I asked whose horses they were—Janes said they were his—I asked why he brought them there to be slaughtered—he said one of</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184402050214"></xptr>
               <p>them, the bay mare, would not work, and the gelding, he bad changed for a donkey and given 16<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. for it at Mitcham-common, on Saturday last, (this was Tuesday)—he said he lived at Mitcham-common—I asked what part of the common—he said, "Grove-place"—I asked how long he had had the mare—he said, "Ever since Barnet fair"—I asked Smith what he had to do with it—he said he met him at Brixton-hill, and lent him a hand to bring the horses there, that was all he knew of it—I asked Janes what this young man had to do with it—he said, "He only assisted me to bring them from Brixton, that is where I met him,"and Smith said he met him at Brixton-hill—I heard Mr. Winkley tell Janes to go to the counting-house and receive his money—I thought it was all right, and they both went away together—I asked them before they left the yard, "Are you now going back to Mitcham?"—Janes said, "Yes"—they stood alongside each other at the time—they went away together—I followed them full half a mile to see if they went in the road for Mitcham—they then went down Poplar-row in a direction for the Kent-road—I followed and stopped them—I asked Janes where he was going, did he call that the road to Mitcham—he said, "I am going to London-bridge to buy this young man a pair of shoes"—I said it was not the road for London-bridge, he had told me a story, I must take him back and be satisfied he had come by the horses honestly—I took them back to Winkley's yard and told them they must go with me to Mitcham—I told Winkley not to slaughter the horses—I took the prisoners in a <hi rend="italic">cab</hi> to Mitcham to see if their statement was true—Janes had said he had <hi rend="italic">chopped</hi> the gelding for a donkey and 16<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. with a man who lived on Mitcham-common—I took them to the place pointed out by Janes—I found the man did not live there, nor did he himself live where he said—I brought them back and took them to the station.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did all the conversation about the horses take place in the yard? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I began it by asking why they brought them there—Winkley stood very near, and heard the best partof the conversation—the prisoners seemed willing to go to Mitcham.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. DOANE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was not all Smith said, that he met him and helped him? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HORRY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did the horses look fit for slaughter? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—they were worn out, and one had the mange.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440205-name-1437" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1437" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1437" type="surname" value="PERSHOUSE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1437" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM PERSHOUSE</persName>
                  </hi>. I live with my father, William Pershouse, a farmer, at Greenwich. He had the mare and gelding turned out on the Charlton marshes all the summer—I saw them there three days or a week before they were taken away—the two were worth 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.;</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Does your father own the vans be<lb></lb>tween Greenwich and Woolwich? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—he has not disposed of his stock, I swear these two horses are his—I saw them in the marshes night and day—they belonged to the farm—I know them by being both blind in the right eye—the gelding knuckles over the hind joint, which had been sprained—I do not think either of them had the mange—I will not swear it, not having been close to them—they were in rather low condition—they might look fit for the knackers, but answered our purpose.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HORRY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Have you seen the mare and gelding? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, the day before yesterday, in the upper field, at Charlton.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440205-name-1438" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1438" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1438" type="surname" value="WEBB"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1438" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>SAMUEL WEBB</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a labourer, in the service of William Pershouse, of Greenwich. On the 3rd of Jan. I was at Winkley's, and saw a mare and geld<lb></lb>ing—they both belong to my master—I saw Harris there—he afterwards gave me the mare and gelding to take home—on the 1st Jan. I had seen them both on the marshes, about half-past three o'clock in the afternoon, in the next marsh to the Anchor and Hope public-house—I missed them about half-past seven</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184402050215"></xptr>
               <p>o'clock on Tuesday morning—I found them at Winkley's on Wednesday, the 3rd of Jan.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi>? <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What do you know them by? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I should know them very well if I saw them a quarter of a mile off by the marks—I have worked with the gelding four years, and have known the other about six months—I am quite sure they are master's—they were on their last legs—Harris, the police-sergeant, was at Winkley's when I taw them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440205-name-1439" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1439" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1439" type="surname" value="TOWN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1439" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM TOWN</persName>
                  </hi>. I keep the Anchor and Hope, at Lewisham. I know the prisoners—I saw them on Monday night, the 1st of Jan., at my house, at late as ten o'clock—my house is not near the marshes—Janes hat lived about 150 yards from me, for about two years and a half—he has a small stable there.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Has he borne an honest character? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I never knew anything against him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440205-name-1440" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1440" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1440" type="surname" value="WEBB"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1440" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES WEBB</persName>
                  </hi>. I live with my father, at Charlton. I know Smith, by going with Pershouse's wagon—on Monday, the 1st of Jan., about three o'clock, or a little after, I saw Smith walking with somebody towards the marshes—they passed through Pershouse's field—Smith hove a snow-ball at my brother—I am quite sure Janes it the one who waa with Smith—I saw him again before the Magistrate.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Did not you say at first, you did not know Janet? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Not before that day—he was about five minutes in my sight—I was at work in the field, about half a mile from Charlton marshes—I did not tee the horses till about half an hour after.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440205-name-1441" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1441" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1441" type="surname" value="RANDLE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1441" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN RANDLE</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman.</hi>) I received the prisoners in charge from Harris on the 2nd of Jan.—I found two sovereigns on Janes.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440205-name-1442" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1442" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1442" type="surname" value="WEBB"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1442" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>SAMUEL WEBB</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> The two marshes are twelve or fourteen acres—master's cattle run there—the marshes communicate—they might run from one to the other—we only had three horses there at that time.</p>
               <p>(Janes received a good character.)</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">JANES</hi>—<hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18440205-793-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-793-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-793-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value="no_subcategory"></interp>GUILTY</rs>
                  </hi>. Aged 26.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">SMITH</hi>—<hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18440205-793-verdict-2" type="verdictDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-793-verdict-2" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-793-verdict-2" type="verdictSubcategory" value="no_subcategory"></interp>GUILTY</rs>
                  </hi>. Aged 25.</p>
